                    )</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1945v07</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d159</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">159</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1945-02-16T20:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1945-02-16T20:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-02-16T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-02-16T20:00:00-05:00" n="159" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d159">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/2–1645: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-02-16T21:00:00-04:00">February 16, 1945—9 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>267. In connection with press reports in today’s and yesterday’s newspapers here
                    of interviews given by Wang Shih-chieh, Chou En-lai and General Wedemeyer, we
                    would appreciate receiving by radio full text of statements made to the press in
                    Chungking by these officials.<note n="85" xml:id="d159fn85">See telegrams Nos.
                        245, 246, and 247, February 18, from the Ambassador in China, <ref target="#pg_231">pp. 231</ref>, <ref target="#pg_232">232</ref> and <ref target="#pg_233">233</ref>.</note>
                    <pb facs="0230" n="220" xml:id="pg_220"/> We would also appreciate receiving in
                    a separate telegram such interpretive comment as you are in a position to make
                    with regard to the statements.<note n="86" xml:id="d159fn86">See telegram No.
                        242, February 18, 11 a.m., from the Ambassador in China, <ref target="#pg_223">p. 223</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
